.TH UTILITYKIT 1 "July 2026" "UtilityKit v5.10.6" "UtilityKit Tools"
.SH NAME
utility-process_killer \- Display a live memory and swap usage overview, list the top processes by memory consumption, and optionally send a signal to terminate a specific process by PID.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B utility process_killer
[\fIoptions\fP]
.SH DESCRIPTION
Display a live memory and swap usage overview, list the top processes by memory consumption, and optionally send a signal to terminate a specific process by PID.
.SH FEATURES
.PP
.IP \(bu 4
\fBMemory overview\fP — shows RAM and swap usage with a color-coded progress bar
.IP \(bu 4
\fBTop process list\fP — displays the 10 highest memory-consuming processes with PID, user, CPU, and memory columns
.IP \(bu 4
\fBProcess termination\fP — sends \fCSIGTERM\fP or \fCSIGKILL\fP to any PID you specify
.IP \(bu 4
\fBExit confirmation\fP — reports whether the process actually stopped after the signal was sent
.IP \(bu 4
\fBInteractive mode\fP — running without arguments shows the overview then prompts for a PID
.PP
.PP
.PP
.SH USAGE
.PP
.EX
bash _process_killer/_process_killer.sh

bash _process_killer/_process_killer.sh

bash _process_killer/_process_killer.sh --pid 1234

bash _process_killer/_process_killer.sh --pid 1234 --signal KILL
.EE
.PP
.PP
.PP
.SH OPTIONS
.PP
Option   |   Description
\fC--pid PID\fP   |   PID of the process to terminate
\fC--signal TERM\  |  KILL\fP   |   Signal to send (default: \fCTERM\fP)
\fC-h, --help\fP   |   Show usage
.PP
.PP
.PP
.SH SIGNAL REFERENCE
.PP
Signal   |   Effect   |   When to use
\fCTERM\fP   |   Polite stop — process can clean up before exiting   |   Always try this first
\fCKILL\fP   |   Forced immediate stop — cannot be ignored or caught   |   Only if TERM has no effect
.PP
.PP
.PP
.SH MEMORY OVERVIEW
.PP
.EX
  Memory overview
  ------------------------------------------------
  RAM    1,823 MB / 7,822 MB  ######------
  Swap     128 MB / 2,048 MB  #-----------
.EE
.PP
RAM usage is shown in green, swap in cyan. The bar fills proportionally to current usage.
.PP
.PP
.PP
.SH TOP PROCESS LIST
.PP
.EX
  Top processes by memory
  ------------------------------------------------
  PID      USER         %CPU   %MEM   COMMAND
  3421     sahil        12.4   18.2   node
  1892     sahil         0.1    9.7   chrome
  4103     root          0.0    4.1   java
.EE
.PP
.PP
.PP
.SH PROCESS TERMINATION OUTPUT
.PP
When a PID is provided the tool describes the target process before sending the signal, then confirms whether it exited:
.PP
.EX
  Target process: 3421 sahil  12.4  18.2 node
  ✔ Sent SIGTERM to PID 3421 and the process exited.
.EE
.PP
If the process is still running after the signal:
.PP
.EX
  ⚠ Signal sent, but PID 3421 is still running.
.EE
.PP
In that case re-run with \fC--signal KILL\fP to force-stop it.
.PP
.PP
.PP
.SH EXIT CODES
.PP
Code   |   Meaning
\fC0\fP   |   Success or inspection only
\fC1\fP   |   PID does not exist or is not visible to the current user
